{"event": "tool_call", "tool": "view", "args": {"file_path": "C:\\QAx\\002\\context-pack\\system\\execution-protocol.md", "limit": 200, "offset": 1000}}
{"event": "tool_result", "tool": "view", "is_error": false, "result": {"status": "success", "file": "C:\\QAx\\002\\context-pack\\system\\execution-protocol.md", "content": "1000: ---\n1001: \n1002: ## 11. Harness Output Sidecar\n1003: \n1004: **Purpose.** The Stepwise harness reads each step's declared outputs from a sidecar JSON file written at a path the harness controls. If this file is missing, the orchestrator records `outputs: {}` in `state.json`, the UI's artifact panel renders empty, and downstream steps cannot pick up output values via propagation. **Artifacts on disk are not enough** — the sidecar is the framework contract between the skill and the orchestrator.\n1005: \n1006: **Applicability.** Any skill that may be invoked by Stepwise. Standalone invocations (no orchestrator) do not need the sidecar — see the trigger gate below.\n1007: \n1008: **When this section applies.** The input prompt contains a `## Run metadata` block with an `output_file = '<absolute path>'` line. If that block is absent (e.g. standalone invocation outside Stepwise), skip the sidecar write entirely.\n1009: \n1010: ---\n1011: \n1012: ### 11.1 Mechanism\n1013: \n1014: ```\n1015: 1. Re-read the prompt's `## Run metadata` block. Copy the path on the\n1016:    `output_file = '...'` line VERBATIM. Do NOT reconstruct it from runId,\n1017:    session name, project name, or any other source — the path the harness\n1018:    wrote there is the path the harness expects to read from.\n1019: \n1020: 2. Re-read the prompt's `## Output parameters` table. For EVERY row in that\n1021:    table, include a key in the JSON object:\n1022:      - key   = the parameter name from the table\n1023:      - value = the resolved value the skill produced for that output\n1024:                (typically the path to the artifact folder or file)\n1025: \n1026: 3. Write that JSON object to the `output_file` path. This is the FINAL file\n1027:    write of the run — strict ordering (see Section 11.4):\n1028:      - AFTER any skill-defined output verification (e.g. file-existence checks).\n1029:      - AFTER Memory Bank session-end writes (Section 4).\n1030:      - AFTER `_progress.json` flipped to `status: COMPLETED` (Section 2 LAST ACTION).\n1031: \n1032: 4. Do NOT emit any tool call after the sidecar write. The next event in the\n1033:    transcript should be the `final_response` summary.\n1034: ```\n1035: \n1036: ---\n1037: \n1038: ### 11.1.1 Path Correctness Rule (mandatory)\n1039: \n1040: The value reported for any output **path** parameter MUST be the **actual on-disk path the skill wrote\n1041: to** — never a re-derived input parameter, never a fresh `value_template` substitution, and never a\n1042: scope-/sibling-adjusted path that was NOT the one actually used for the write.\n1043: \n1044: ```\n1045: BEFORE writing the sidecar, for every path-typed output parameter:\n1046:   1. Confirm the artifact exists at the path you are about to report\n1047:      (e.g. `ls <PATH>/<EXPECTED-FILE>*` or a stat/existence check).\n1048:   2. If the path the skill actually wrote to differs from the input parameter\n1049:      for ANY reason — sibling-folder rule, scope adjustment, feature_id stripping,\n1050:      SESSION_ID derivation — report the ACTUAL written path, NOT the parameter.\n1051:   3. Reporting a parameter you did not write to is the documented cause of the\n1052:      duplicate-artifact-on-REPAIR defect: a later REPAIR run is handed the wrong\n1053:      folder, finds no prior artifact, and silently rebuilds a duplicate. (See §7.)\n1054: ```\n1055: \n1056: **Worked example (sibling rule).** A planning step receives `planning_output_path =\n1057: /base/code-development/code-task-planning` but, because `feature_id` was empty and the upstream research\n1058: was scoped, Step 1 actually wrote to `/base/code-development/TICKET-001/code-task-planning/`. The sidecar\n1059: MUST report the latter (the path that holds the files), never the flat input parameter.\n1060: \n1061: > **Note for skill authors:** \"report the parameter VERBATIM\" guidance (used by some skills to avoid\n1062: > pre-resolution double-prefixing) means *do not re-prepend project/scope segments yourself* — it does\n1063: > NOT license reporting a path you did not write to. When your own logic diverges from the parameter,\n1064: > the actual written path always wins.\n1065: \n1066: ---\n1067: \n1068: ### 11.2 Example\n1069: \n1070: For a skill that declares a single output parameter named `foo_output_path`:\n1071: \n1072: ```json\n1073: { \"foo_output_path\": \"/abs/path/to/artifacts/outputs/<capability>/<step>\" }\n1074: ```\n1075: \n1076: For a skill with multiple output parameters, include every row from the `## Output parameters` table — one key per row. The skill-specific parameter names live in each SKILL.md (Section 11.5); this section does not enumerate them.\n1077: \n1078: ---\n1079: \n1080: ### 11.3 Violation\n1081: \n1082: Ending a Stepwise run with a `final_response` summary that lists the generated artifacts but no sidecar write breaks output propagation. The harness MAY have a `value_template` fallback for specific outputs, but that fallback is not guaranteed for every skill / every output. Treat the sidecar write as **non-optional** whenever the `## Run metadata` block is present in the prompt — do not rely on the fallback.\n1083: \n1084: Skills whose outputs lack a `value_template` fallback fail **silently** when the sidecar is missing: downstream steps see `outputs: {}` and propagate empty values; no error surfaces in the run. This is the failure mode this section prevents.\n1085: \n1086: ---\n1087: \n1088: ### 11.4 Composition with Section 2 LAST ACTION\n1089: \n1090: The sidecar write extends Section 2's LAST ACTION; it does NOT replace it. Strict ordering for any Stepwise-invoked skill:\n1091: \n1092: 1. All skill-specific outputs written and verified.\n1093: 2. Memory Bank writes (Section 4 — `active-context.md`, `progress.md`).\n1094: 3. `_progress.json` flipped to `status: COMPLETED` (Section 2 LAST ACTION).\n1095: 4. **Sidecar write** (this section) — final file write of the run.\n1096: 5. `final_response` summary — no further tool calls.\n1097: \n1098: If the skill is invoked standalone (no `## Run metadata` block), step 4 is skipped. Steps 1–3 and 5 still apply.\n1099: \n1100: ---\n1101: \n1102: ### 11.5 Skill-Level Enforcement\n1103: \n1104: Section 11 cannot enumerate output parameter names — those are declared per-skill in the capability YAML's `outputs` block and surface in each prompt's `## Output parameters` table. Each SKILL.md MUST include a short inline callout naming its output parameters, so the agent knows which keys to put in the sidecar JSON without parsing the YAML.\n1105: \n1106: Recommended SKILL.md callout shape:\n1107: \n1108: > **Step N: Emit harness outputs sidecar — apply execution-protocol.md Section 11.**\n1109: >\n1110: > **Output parameters this skill produces** (one key per row of the prompt's `## Output parameters` table):\n1111: >\n1112: > - `<param_name_1>`: <one-line description of the resolved value, e.g. \"the resolved output folder path written in earlier steps\">\n1113: > - `<param_name_2>`: ...\n1114: >\n1115: > Example sidecar contents (illustrative):\n1116: >\n1117: > ```json\n1118: > { \"<param_name_1>\": \"/abs/path/...\", \"<param_name_2>\": \"...\" }\n1119: > ```\n1120: \n1121: The callout is intentionally short. Trigger gate, mechanism, ordering, and violation rule all live in Section 11 — the SKILL.md only names the keys.\n1122: \n1123: ---\n1124: \n1125: ## 12. Delegated Exploration\n1126: \n1127: **Purpose.** Broad, read-only exploration — locating which files implement a feature, mapping every call site of a symbol, diffing two branches, enumerating what a PR changed, surveying naming conventions across a module, or sweeping a large set of input artifacts (briefs, PRDs, epics, prior specs) — can be **delegated to a read-only exploration subagent** instead of being done inline by the main agent. The subagent reads broadly and returns a compact conclusion; the main agent keeps its context lean for the synthesis and writing it alone is responsible for. This is an **optimization of the input-loading / research phase**, not a new deliverable.\n1128: \n1129: **Why it helps.** It directly serves the same goal as §5 (FIC context monitoring): a fan-out read that would otherwise fill the main context with file contents instead returns as a short summary, so the main agent stays in its healthy utilization band and can do more synthesis before any compaction. Running the sweep on a cheaper/faster model (see §12.3) also makes exploration materially cheaper than reading every file in the main session.\n1130: \n1131: **Applicability.** Any skill whose route includes §12. This section is **capability-gated and harness-agnostic**: it applies *only if the running harness exposes a read-only exploration subagent* (the mechanism and its name differ across harnesses — a built-in \"explore\"/\"search\" agent, a task/agent spawn tool, etc.). If the harness exposes no such capability, follow §12.5 (inline fallback) and change nothing else. **Never name a specific tool, agent, or model ID in a skill** — describe the capability and let each harness bind it.\n1132: \n1133: **When this section applies in the run order.** Exploration happens during input loading / research, *before* spec generation (§10) or review. In the routing rule §12 therefore sits early — after §2, before §10 / §10.5.\n1134: \n1135: ---\n1136: \n1137: ### 12.1 When to delegate (and when not)\n1138: \n1139: **Delegate when** the work is a broad, read-only sweep where you need the *conclusion*, not the raw contents:\n1140: - \"Which files implement / touch capability X?\"\n1141: - \"Find every call site / consumer of symbol Y.\"\n1142: - \"What changed in branch A compared to branch B / on this PR?\"\n1143: - \"What are the naming and structural conventions across this module?\"\n1144: - \"Across these N input artifacts, which ones mention requirement Z, and where?\"\n1145: - Several independent search angles that can run in parallel.\n1146: \n1147: **Do NOT delegate:**\n1148: - The **analysis, root-cause reasoning, decision, or spec-writing** — those are the skill's deliverable and stay with the main agent.\n1149: - Work that **mutates files** — the exploration subagent is read-only. Edits, scaffolding, and writes are never delegated through §12.\n1150: - Cases where **scope is already a single known file or a tight, named path** — just read it inline; a subagent round-trip adds latency for no context savings.\n1151: - Anything that would have the subagent make a **judgment the skill is accountable for** (e.g. \"decide the fix\", \"rank the options\"). Ask it for facts and locations, not verdicts.\n1152: \n1153: The **execution-path / scope constraint each skill already enforces still applies** — delegating does not grant the subagent unrestricted repo access. Pass it the same bounded scope the main agent would have used.\n1154: \n1155: ---\n1156: \n1157: ### 12.2 The return contract\n1158: \n1159: Instruct the subagent to return **conclusions plus `file:line` pointers and a compact summary — never file dumps or pasted source**. A good delegated prompt:\n1160: - States one bounded, specific question (not \"explore the codebase\").\n1161: - Names the scope / path constraint to stay within.\n1162: - Asks explicitly for: the answer, the precise `file:line` references that support it, and a short summary — and asks it NOT to paste large file contents back.\n1163: \n1164: The returned summary is consumed as **research input** to the main session — the same role inline exploration notes would have played.\n1165: \n1166: ---\n1167: \n1168: ### 12.3 Model selection\n1169: \n1170: Exploration is search and retrieval, not synthesis — a **cheaper / faster model tier is sufficient and materially cheaper**. When the harness lets you pick the subagent's model, prefer its fast/economy tier (the harness's equivalent of a \"fast\" or \"mini\" model) for §12 sweeps. Reserve the strong model for the synthesis the main agent does. Describe this as a preference for the cheap tier — do not hardcode a model ID, since the available tiers differ per harness.\n1171: \n1172: ---\n1173: \n1174: ### 12.4 Verify before use\n1175: \n1176: Subagent output is **input, not ground truth**. The **Zero-Invention Policy still governs the main agent's deliverable**: before citing a `file:line` in a spec, basing a fix or plan step on a delegated finding, or asserting a fact the subagent reported, the main agent MUST confirm the pointer actually exists (open it / re-grep it). A subagent hallucination that flows unverified into the deliverable is still an invention by the skill. Treat delegated findings exactly as you would treat any unverified source: confirm, then use.\n1177: \n1178: ---\n1179: \n1180: ### 12.5 Fallback — no subagent capability\n1181: \n1182: If the harness exposes no read-only exploration subagent, the skill performs the same exploration **inline**, bounded by its execution-path / scope constraint, exactly as before this section existed. §12 is **never a requirement and never changes the deliverable**: a skill must produce identical-quality output whether or not delegation was available. Do not block, warn, or degrade when the capability is absent — simply explore inline.\n1183: \n1184: ---\n1185: \n1186: ### 12.6 Skill-Level Enforcement\n1187: \n1188: Each SKILL.md routed to §12 includes a short callout at its input-loading / exploration step pointing here. Recommended callout shape:\n1189: \n1190: > **During input loading / exploration — apply execution-protocol.md Section 12 (Delegated Exploration) if your harness supports it.**\n1191: >\n1192: > Broad read-only sweeps for this skill (e.g. <one or two skill-specific examples: \"locating the files on the bug's execution path\", \"diffing the feature branch against the base\", \"surveying which input artifacts cover each requirement\">) MAY be delegated to a read-only exploration subagent on a cheap/fast model, which returns conclusions + `file:line` pointers (not file dumps). Synthesis, decisions, and all writing stay with this agent, which verifies any delegated `file:line` before using it (Zero-Invention still applies). If no subagent capability exists, explore inline under the usual scope constraint — output quality is identical either way.\n1193: \n1194: The callout is intentionally short. The when/when-not rules, return contract, model preference, verification duty, and fallback all live in Section 12 — the SKILL.md only names the skill-specific sweep examples.\n1195: \n1196: ---\n1197: \n1198: ## 13. Code-Location Discipline\n1199: ", "metadata": {"start_line": 1000, "end_line": 1199, "returned_lines": 200, "has_more": true, "eof_reached": false, "truncated": false}}}
